1
00:01:57,964 --> 00:02:00,392
Hey. Pull up at the corner.

2
00:02:13,480 --> 00:02:15,113
Wait here.

3
00:02:22,155 --> 00:02:23,539
How.

4
00:02:23,698 --> 00:02:25,830
Good afternoon, sir.

5
00:02:57,357 --> 00:02:58,776
Yes?

6
00:02:59,151 --> 00:03:02,778
I'd like to see the boss. What'd you say his name is?

7
00:03:02,779 --> 00:03:05,491
- I didn't say. - Cagey, huh?

8
00:03:06,366 --> 00:03:08,033
Mr Boot is the owner and publisher.

9
00:03:08,034 --> 00:03:11,370
Okay. Tell Mr Boot Mr Tatum would like to see him.

10
00:03:11,371 --> 00:03:13,873
Charles Tatum from New York.

11
00:03:13,874 --> 00:03:15,553
What about?

12
00:03:16,168 --> 00:03:17,501
Look, fan, just ask him,

13
00:03:17,502 --> 00:03:20,843
how would he like to make himself a fast $200 a week?

14
00:03:21,339 --> 00:03:23,716
What did you say you were selling? Insurance?

15
00:03:23,717 --> 00:03:25,480
I didn't say.

16
00:03:25,927 --> 00:03:27,642
Cagey, huh?

17
00:03:52,621 --> 00:03:55,289
Now, isn't that something? Who said it?

18
00:03:55,290 --> 00:03:58,429
Well, Mr Boot said it, but I did the needlework.

19
00:03:58,585 --> 00:03:59,752
Oh!

20
00:03:59,753 --> 00:04:02,963
- Okay. - I wish I could coin them like that.

21
00:04:02,964 --> 00:04:05,226
If I ever do, would you embroider it for me?

22
00:04:10,972 --> 00:04:12,431
- Mr Tatum? - Yes, sir.

23
00:04:12,432 --> 00:04:13,808
Go ahead. What is it?

24
00:04:13,809 --> 00:04:16,310
Well, Mr Boot, I was passing through Albuquerque.

25
00:04:16,311 --> 00:04:19,188
Had breakfast here. Read your paper.

26
00:04:19,189 --> 00:04:20,898
Thought you might be interested in my reaction.

27
00:04:20,899 --> 00:04:24,370
- You bet I am. - Well, sir, it made me throw up.

28
00:04:25,028 --> 00:04:27,905
I don't want you to think I expected The New York Times.

29
00:04:27,906 --> 00:04:30,908
But even for Albuquerque, this is pretty Albuquerque.

30
00:04:30,909 --> 00:04:32,743
All right. Here's your nickel back.

31
00:04:32,744 --> 00:04:35,704
Now, what's all this about my making $200 a week?

32
00:04:35,705 --> 00:04:37,415
Apparently, you're not familiar with my name.

33
00:04:37,416 --> 00:04:38,666
Can't say that I am.

34
00:04:38,667 --> 00:04:40,835
That's because you don't get the eastern papers out here.

35
00:04:40,836 --> 00:04:42,002
I thought maybe once in a while

36
00:04:42,003 --> 00:04:43,712
somebody would toss one out of the Super Chief

37
00:04:43,713 --> 00:04:45,673
and you might've seen my byline.

38
00:04:45,674 --> 00:04:49,635
Charles Tatum? Worked New York, Chicago, Detroit...

39
00:04:49,636 --> 00:04:52,894
- What about the $200? - I was coming to that.

40
00:04:54,266 --> 00:04:57,322
Mr Boot, I'm a $250-a-week newspaperman.

41
00:04:57,727 --> 00:05:00,604
- I can be had for $50. - Why are you so good to me?

42
00:05:00,605 --> 00:05:03,107
I know newspapers backward, forward and sideways.

43
00:05:03,108 --> 00:05:05,693
I can write them, edit them, print them, wrap them and sell them.

44
00:05:05,694 --> 00:05:08,988
- Don't need anybody right now. - I can handle big news and little news.

45
00:05:08,989 --> 00:05:12,662
And if there's no news, I'll go out and bite a dog.

46
00:05:14,077 --> 00:05:17,466
- Make it $45. - What makes you so cheap?

47
00:05:18,582 --> 00:05:22,585
A fair question, considering I've been top man wherever I've worked.

48
00:05:22,586 --> 00:05:24,879
You'll be glad to know that I've been fired from 11 papers

49
00:05:24,880 --> 00:05:27,590
with a total circulation of seven million,

50
00:05:27,591 --> 00:05:30,176
for reasons with which I don't want to bore you.

51
00:05:30,177 --> 00:05:32,224
Go ahead. Bore me.

52
00:05:36,057 --> 00:05:39,894
I'm a pretty good liar. I've done a lot of lying in my time.

53
00:05:39,895 --> 00:05:42,897
I've lied to men who wear belts. I've lied to men who wear suspenders.

54
00:05:42,898 --> 00:05:44,690
But I'd never be so stupid as to lie to a man

55
00:05:44,691 --> 00:05:47,401
who wears both belt and suspenders.

56
00:05:47,402 --> 00:05:50,988
- How's that again? - You strike me as a cautious man.

57
00:05:50,989 --> 00:05:53,699
A man who checks and double-checks.

58
00:05:53,700 --> 00:05:55,951
So I'll tell you why I was fired.

59
00:05:55,952 --> 00:05:58,496
In New York, a story of mine brought on a libel suit.

60
00:05:58,497 --> 00:06:02,458
In Chicago, I started something with the publisher's wife.

61
00:06:02,459 --> 00:06:04,710
In Detroit, I was caught drinking out of season.

62
00:06:04,711 --> 00:06:07,553
- In Cleveland... - I get the picture.

63
00:06:07,756 --> 00:06:11,300
Now, then I find myself in Albuquerque with no money.

64
00:06:11,301 --> 00:06:15,188
A burnt-out bearing, bad tyres and a lousy reputation.

65
00:06:15,305 --> 00:06:17,014
Bad tyres can be dangerous.

66
00:06:17,015 --> 00:06:19,266
I've only one chance to get back where I belong.

67
00:06:19,267 --> 00:06:21,811
To land a job on a small-town paper like yours

68
00:06:21,812 --> 00:06:25,022
and wait and hope and pray for something big to break,

69
00:06:25,023 --> 00:06:27,066
something I can latch on to,

70
00:06:27,067 --> 00:06:30,528
something the wire services will gobble up and yell for more.

71
00:06:30,529 --> 00:06:35,459
Just one good beat, a Tatum special, and they'll roll out the red carpet.

72
00:06:35,867 --> 00:06:39,620
Because when they need you, they forgive and forget.

73
00:06:39,621 --> 00:06:40,746
But until then, Mr Boot,

74
00:06:40,747 --> 00:06:44,670
you'll get yourself the best newspaperman you ever had.

75
00:06:44,709 --> 00:06:47,931
- At $40 per. When do I start? - Don't push.

76
00:06:49,131 --> 00:06:52,133
- I hope I haven't scared you off. - Well, I don't know.

77
00:06:52,134 --> 00:06:55,219
I'm not afraid of a libel suit, because I'm a lawyer myself.

78
00:06:55,220 --> 00:06:57,304
Check and double-check every word I print.

79
00:06:57,305 --> 00:06:58,973
Sure. Belt and suspenders.

80
00:06:58,974 --> 00:07:00,558
Now, about that publisher's wife,

81
00:07:00,559 --> 00:07:03,394
I think you should know Mrs Boot is a grandmother three times.

82
00:07:03,395 --> 00:07:06,272
If you wanna start something with her, she'd be very flattered.

83
00:07:06,273 --> 00:07:08,649
And as for drinking, do you drink a lot?

84
00:07:08,650 --> 00:07:10,484
Not a lot. Just frequently.

85
00:07:10,485 --> 00:07:13,821
We have a shop rule here, no liquor on the premises.

86
00:07:13,822 --> 00:07:16,073
- How about smoking? - Of course.

87
00:07:16,074 --> 00:07:19,048
And I pay $60 a week in this shop.

88
00:07:19,995 --> 00:07:21,758
I'll take it.

89
00:07:24,666 --> 00:07:25,916
Where's my desk?

90
00:07:25,917 --> 00:07:29,887
The one by the door. You may be out of here by Saturday.

91
00:07:30,797 --> 00:07:33,011
The sooner the better.

92
00:07:59,785 --> 00:08:03,505
Thanks, Geronimo. Take these over to the engraver's.

93
00:08:04,039 --> 00:08:05,539
What's this mess?

94
00:08:05,540 --> 00:08:07,124
They haven't got any chopped chicken livers.

95
00:08:07,125 --> 00:08:08,626
I brought you some chicken tacos.

96
00:08:08,627 --> 00:08:10,002
Chicken tacos?

97
00:08:10,003 --> 00:08:11,796
They're not gonna chop the livers any more for you.

98
00:08:11,797 --> 00:08:15,636
Nobody else will buy them. And no more garlic pickles.

99
00:08:18,637 --> 00:08:21,472
When the history of this sun-baked Siberia is written,

100
00:08:21,473 --> 00:08:24,308
these shameful words will live in infamy.

101
00:08:24,309 --> 00:08:26,772
"No chopped chicken liver."

102
00:08:28,772 --> 00:08:30,868
"No garlic pickles."

103
00:08:31,858 --> 00:08:35,532
No Lindy's. No Madison Square Garden.

104
00:08:35,695 --> 00:08:37,542
No Yogi Berra.

105
00:08:38,740 --> 00:08:41,242
What do you know about Yogi Berra, Miss Deverich?

106
00:08:41,243 --> 00:08:43,577
- I beg your pardon? - Yogi Berra!

107
00:08:43,578 --> 00:08:46,747
Yogi? Why, it's a sort of religion, isn't it?

108
00:08:46,748 --> 00:08:50,635
You bet it is. A belief in the New York Yankees.

109
00:08:51,711 --> 00:08:54,380
You know what's wrong with New Mexico, Mr Wendel?

110
00:08:54,381 --> 00:08:56,428
Too much outdoors.

111
00:08:57,217 --> 00:09:01,804
Give me those eight spindly trees in front of Rockefeller Center any day.

112
00:09:01,805 --> 00:09:04,398
That's enough outdoors for me.

113
00:09:04,766 --> 00:09:08,356
No subways smelling sweet-sour.

114
00:09:09,646 --> 00:09:12,690
What do you use for noise around here?

115
00:09:12,691 --> 00:09:15,276
No beautiful roar from eight million ants,

116
00:09:15,277 --> 00:09:17,657
fighting, cursing, loving.

117
00:09:18,739 --> 00:09:21,664
No shows. No South Pacific.

118
00:09:22,492 --> 00:09:26,296
No chic little dames across a crowded bar.

119
00:09:27,998 --> 00:09:29,248
And worst of all, Herbie,

120
00:09:29,249 --> 00:09:32,803
no 80th floor to jump from when you feel like it.

121
00:09:33,253 --> 00:09:35,713
Is this one of your long-playing records, Chuck?

122
00:09:35,714 --> 00:09:38,094
Let's hear the other side.

123
00:09:38,759 --> 00:09:41,470
All right. I'll play it for you.

124
00:09:41,762 --> 00:09:46,599
When I came here, I thought this was gonna be a 30-day stretch, maybe 60.

125
00:09:46,600 --> 00:09:48,517
Now it's a year.

126
00:09:48,518 --> 00:09:50,686
It looks like a life sentence.

127
00:09:50,687 --> 00:09:54,482
Where is it? Where's the loaf of bread with a file in it?

128
00:09:54,483 --> 00:09:57,823
Where's that big story to get me out of here?

129
00:09:58,695 --> 00:10:01,489
One year, and what's our hot news?

130
00:10:01,490 --> 00:10:03,454
A soapbox derby.

131
00:10:04,493 --> 00:10:08,213
A tornado that double-crossed us and went to Texas.

132
00:10:08,789 --> 00:10:12,208
An old goof who said he was the real Jesse James,

133
00:10:12,209 --> 00:10:14,460
until they found out he was a chicken thief from Gallup

134
00:10:14,461 --> 00:10:17,256
by the name of Schimmelmacher.

135
00:10:18,673 --> 00:10:22,596
I'm stuck here, fans. Stuck for good!

136
00:10:24,679 --> 00:10:26,222
Unless, of course, you, Miss Deverich,

137
00:10:26,223 --> 00:10:28,307
Unless, of course, you, Miss Deverich,

138
00:10:28,308 --> 00:10:30,267
instead of writing household hints

139
00:10:30,268 --> 00:10:33,270
about how to remove chilli stains from blue jeans,

140
00:10:33,271 --> 00:10:36,446
get yourself involved in a trunk murder.

141
00:10:36,691 --> 00:10:38,943
How about it, Miss Deverich?

142
00:10:38,944 --> 00:10:42,332
I could do wonders with your dismembered body.

143
00:10:42,614 --> 00:10:45,290
Oh, Mr Tatum. Really.

144
00:10:48,370 --> 00:10:50,501
Or you, Mr Wendel.

145
00:10:51,039 --> 00:10:53,874
If you'd only toss that cigar out of the window,

146
00:10:53,875 --> 00:10:58,671
real far, all the way to Los Alamos,

147
00:10:58,672 --> 00:11:00,304
and boom!

148
00:11:02,259 --> 00:11:04,721
Now there would be a story.

149
00:11:05,720 --> 00:11:10,141
I told you no liquor in the office. I thought I could trust you.

150
00:11:10,142 --> 00:11:13,400
What a suspicious nature you have, Mr Boot.

151
00:11:16,481 --> 00:11:18,399
Pretty, isn't it? I make those things

152
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:21,026
every night when I go home out of matches and toothpicks.

153
00:11:21,027 --> 00:11:22,956
Calms my nerves.

154
00:11:23,029 --> 00:11:25,576
Sorry, Tatum.

155
00:11:26,241 --> 00:11:28,826
- Maybe you do need a change. - Do I.

156
00:11:28,827 --> 00:11:32,955
And I got news for you. You're going out of town for a couple of days.

157
00:11:32,956 --> 00:11:35,875
- How far and in what direction? - Los Barrios county.

158
00:11:35,876 --> 00:11:38,586
They're having a rattlesnake hunt, and I want you to cover it.

159
00:11:38,587 --> 00:11:40,629
- A rattlesnake hunt? - That's right.

160
00:11:40,630 --> 00:11:43,716
And take Herbie along. Let's get some art.

161
00:11:43,717 --> 00:11:47,428
A rattlesnake hunt. Well, isn't that ginger-peachy?

162
00:11:47,429 --> 00:11:50,014
A real "stop the press, pull out the front page",

163
00:11:50,015 --> 00:11:51,599
"get ready to re-plate" assignment.

164
00:11:51,600 --> 00:11:53,726
Have a nice time, Chuck. See the country.

165
00:11:53,727 --> 00:11:56,949
And don't worry, I'll put the paper to bed.

166
00:11:59,107 --> 00:12:03,789
Well, it looks like we're starting our second year with a real bang.

167
00:12:03,987 --> 00:12:06,083
Okay, fan, pack up.

168
00:12:15,791 --> 00:12:17,833
You know, this could be a pretty good story, Chuck.

169
00:12:17,834 --> 00:12:19,794
Don't sell it short.

170
00:12:19,795 --> 00:12:21,962
It's quite a sight, 1,000 rattlers in the underbrush,

171
00:12:21,963 --> 00:12:24,757
and a lot of men smoking them out, bashing in their heads.

172
00:12:24,758 --> 00:12:28,229
Big deal, 1,000 rattlers in the underbrush.

173
00:12:31,098 --> 00:12:34,438
Give me just 50 of them loose in Albuquerque.

174
00:12:35,102 --> 00:12:37,686
Like that leopard in Oklahoma City.

175
00:12:37,687 --> 00:12:39,980
The whole town in panic.

176
00:12:39,981 --> 00:12:42,990
Deserted streets. Barricaded houses.

177
00:12:43,443 --> 00:12:45,945
They're evacuating the children.

178
00:12:45,946 --> 00:12:48,041
Every man is armed.

179
00:12:48,573 --> 00:12:51,369
Fifty killers on the prowl. Fifty.

180
00:12:52,077 --> 00:12:55,216
One by one, they start hunting them down.

181
00:12:55,372 --> 00:12:57,301
They get 10, 20.

182
00:12:57,624 --> 00:13:00,882
It's building. They get 40, 45. They get 49.

183
00:13:01,044 --> 00:13:03,424
Where's the last rattler?

184
00:13:03,755 --> 00:13:08,426
In a kindergarten? In a church? In a crowded elevator? Where?

185
00:13:08,427 --> 00:13:10,439
I give up. Where?

186
00:13:11,012 --> 00:13:13,523
In my desk drawer, fan.

187
00:13:14,808 --> 00:13:17,017
Stashed away, only nobody knows it, see?

188
00:13:17,018 --> 00:13:19,103
The story's good for another three days.

189
00:13:19,104 --> 00:13:22,148
Then when I'm good and ready, we come out with a big extra.

190
00:13:22,149 --> 00:13:24,778
"Sun-Bulletin snags number 50."

191
00:13:24,985 --> 00:13:27,531
Where do you get those ideas?

192
00:13:27,779 --> 00:13:32,496
Herbie, boy, how long did you go to that school of journalism?

193
00:13:32,576 --> 00:13:34,339
Three years.

194
00:13:34,578 --> 00:13:37,005
Three years down the drain.

195
00:13:38,331 --> 00:13:41,625
Me, I didn't go to any college, but I know what makes a good story.

196
00:13:41,626 --> 00:13:43,210
Because before I ever worked on a paper,

197
00:13:43,211 --> 00:13:45,296
I sold them on a street corner.

198
00:13:45,297 --> 00:13:49,646
You know the first thing I found out? Bad news sells best.

199
00:13:50,969 --> 00:13:53,562
Because good news is no news.

200
00:13:54,514 --> 00:13:56,645
Better get some gas.

201
00:14:17,162 --> 00:14:19,174
Hey! Anybody here?

202
00:14:22,125 --> 00:14:23,509
Hey!

203
00:14:35,388 --> 00:14:36,938
Service!

204
00:14:43,647 --> 00:14:45,445
Anybody home?

205
00:14:58,286 --> 00:15:00,667
Sorry to bother you, lady.

206
00:15:04,334 --> 00:15:06,714
I'd like to buy some gas.

207
00:15:25,230 --> 00:15:28,232
Hey, there's something screwy about this place.

208
00:15:28,233 --> 00:15:30,245
There's just an old lady in there that's...

209
00:15:41,246 --> 00:15:44,123
Now, what would the law be doing up there in that old Indian cliff dwelling?

210
00:15:44,124 --> 00:15:47,376
Maybe they got a warrant for Sitting Bull for that Custer rap.

211
00:15:47,377 --> 00:15:50,045
Come on, Herbie, let's go visiting. It's for free.

212
00:15:50,046 --> 00:15:52,173
I can get the gas on the way back.

213
00:15:52,174 --> 00:15:54,008
That is, if she's stopped praying.

214
00:15:54,009 --> 00:15:56,051
- Who? - That old lady in there.

215
00:15:56,052 --> 00:15:57,762
What's she praying for?

216
00:15:57,763 --> 00:16:02,349
I don't know, but whatever she's praying for she's sure praying hard.

217
00:16:02,350 --> 00:16:05,146
Maybe it ties in. Let's see.

218
00:16:21,995 --> 00:16:23,954
Oh, I thought you were the doctor.

219
00:16:23,955 --> 00:16:25,414
What's the matter? Somebody hurt?

220
00:16:25,415 --> 00:16:28,667
We don't know yet. He's way in there, under that mountain.

221
00:16:28,668 --> 00:16:31,170
- What happened? - We had a cave-in this morning.

222
00:16:31,171 --> 00:16:32,880
Oh. That so?

223
00:16:32,881 --> 00:16:35,007
Dumb cluck. Everybody keeps telling him,

224
00:16:35,008 --> 00:16:37,134
"Stay out of that place. Stay out of there."

225
00:16:37,135 --> 00:16:39,011
Not Leo. Stubborn like a mule.

226
00:16:39,012 --> 00:16:41,847
He always keeps going back, digging for those Indian pots.

227
00:16:41,848 --> 00:16:44,192
- Who's Leo? - My husband.

228
00:16:45,727 --> 00:16:47,027
Oh.

229
00:16:47,104 --> 00:16:50,658
Well, I'm sorry to hear about it. Hop in.

230
00:17:02,661 --> 00:17:05,171
- You live around here? - Yeah.

231
00:17:05,372 --> 00:17:06,872
I'm Mrs Leo Minosa.

232
00:17:06,873 --> 00:17:09,792
We own that trading post down on the highway.

233
00:17:09,793 --> 00:17:12,588
Finest store in downtown Escudero.

234
00:17:12,754 --> 00:17:15,798
Is that what they call this place? Escudero?

235
00:17:15,799 --> 00:17:18,342
Got a couple of other names for it myself.

236
00:17:18,343 --> 00:17:22,138
Did the Indians really live in that place 450 years ago?

237
00:17:22,139 --> 00:17:25,015
I wouldn't know. I haven't been around that long.

238
00:17:25,016 --> 00:17:27,148
Only seems that long.

239
00:17:27,561 --> 00:17:30,354
Say, if you gents stopped by to see that broken-down cliff dwelling,

240
00:17:30,355 --> 00:17:32,815
you sure picked a swell day.

241
00:17:32,816 --> 00:17:34,734
All right, let's have the facts. You're his father?

242
00:17:34,735 --> 00:17:36,694
Yes. I'm his father.

243
00:17:36,695 --> 00:17:40,700
- How long has he been inside? - Pretty near six hours now.

244
00:17:40,949 --> 00:17:42,742
How far down you think he is?

245
00:17:42,743 --> 00:17:46,746
Oh, about 250 or 300 foot, I should judge.

246
00:17:46,747 --> 00:17:49,582
Best we could do was to get in about halfway.

247
00:17:49,583 --> 00:17:53,461
You got to watch yourself. Swing that pick too hard in them old walls,

248
00:17:53,462 --> 00:17:56,380
you start a sand slide and block up the whole place.

249
00:17:56,381 --> 00:17:58,429
Then goodbye, Leo.

250
00:18:03,680 --> 00:18:05,264
Is that coffee good and hot, Lorraine?

251
00:18:05,265 --> 00:18:08,058
Sure, it's hot. The sandwiches are in the blanket. So are the cigars.

252
00:18:08,059 --> 00:18:10,394
- How's Mama? - All right, I guess.

253
00:18:10,395 --> 00:18:13,731
- How do I find my way? - Just follow our rope. We left it in there.

254
00:18:13,732 --> 00:18:16,609
After that, holler. He'll yell back.

255
00:18:16,610 --> 00:18:18,705
Wait a minute, you.

256
00:18:19,154 --> 00:18:21,238
Nobody goes no place here without I say so.

257
00:18:21,239 --> 00:18:24,325
He's cold. He's hungry. We've got to let him know we're doing something.

258
00:18:24,326 --> 00:18:27,203
Look, I got my hands full already without having two of you in there.

259
00:18:27,204 --> 00:18:30,331
- Somebody's got to go. - How about those Indians?

260
00:18:30,332 --> 00:18:33,918
What do you say, chief? You ought to know your way around here pretty well.

261
00:18:33,919 --> 00:18:36,337
They won't go in. They never do.

262
00:18:36,338 --> 00:18:38,464
- Bad spirits. - Ah, go on.

263
00:18:38,465 --> 00:18:40,762
What are you holding out for, a couple of bucks?

264
00:18:42,677 --> 00:18:44,178
He says it's their holy mountain. The mountain of the seven vultures.

265
00:18:44,179 --> 00:18:46,680
He says it's their holy mountain. The mountain of the seven vultures.

266
00:18:46,681 --> 00:18:51,114
The mountain of the seven vultures. It's got a sound to it.

267
00:18:52,479 --> 00:18:54,906
Get me a few shots, Herbie.

268
00:18:59,736 --> 00:19:02,571
Looks like it's your move, copper. What's it gonna be?

269
00:19:02,572 --> 00:19:04,657
I'm thinking. Don't rush me. I'll do something.

270
00:19:04,658 --> 00:19:09,745
You could always give that poor fellow in there a ticket for parking overtime.

271
00:19:09,746 --> 00:19:11,038
Let me have those things.

272
00:19:11,039 --> 00:19:12,331
Who do you think you are butting in like this?

273
00:19:12,332 --> 00:19:13,999
- Let me have your flashlight. - Who is he?

274
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:16,627
I'll tell you who I am. I'm the guy who's going in that cave.

275
00:19:16,628 --> 00:19:18,546
And you're the guy that's been sounding off long enough.

276
00:19:18,547 --> 00:19:19,755
Now give me your flashlight.

277
00:19:19,756 --> 00:19:21,934
- Why, you... - Shut up.

278
00:19:22,175 --> 00:19:24,104
Come on, Herbie.

279
00:19:25,929 --> 00:19:27,513
Thanks, mister, and God bless you.

280
00:19:27,514 --> 00:19:29,598
Tell him we'll get him out. Tell him not to worry.

281
00:19:29,599 --> 00:19:30,766
- Sure. - Okay.

282
00:19:30,767 --> 00:19:32,977
And tell him we'll have a big coming-out party for him

283
00:19:32,978 --> 00:19:35,738
with a brass band and everything.

284
00:20:05,469 --> 00:20:07,397
Here's the rope.

285
00:20:07,512 --> 00:20:09,856
I hope we can get to him.

286
00:20:09,931 --> 00:20:11,350
Yeah.

287
00:20:17,439 --> 00:20:19,819
Watch out for those rocks.

288
00:20:27,699 --> 00:20:29,867
The old man sure looked bad.

289
00:20:29,868 --> 00:20:32,379
- Did you see his face? - Yeah.

290
00:20:33,121 --> 00:20:36,540
Like the faces of those folks you see outside a coal mine

291
00:20:36,541 --> 00:20:39,337
with maybe 84 men trapped inside.

292
00:20:39,419 --> 00:20:43,223
One man's better than 84. Didn't they teach you that?

293
00:20:43,507 --> 00:20:46,183
- Teach me what? - Human interest.

294
00:20:46,551 --> 00:20:51,013
You pick up the paper, you read about 84 men or 284,

295
00:20:51,014 --> 00:20:53,265
or a million men, like in the Chinese famine.

296
00:20:53,266 --> 00:20:56,018
You read it, but it doesn't stay with you.

297
00:20:56,019 --> 00:21:00,147
One man's different. You wanna know all about him. That's human interest.

298
00:21:00,148 --> 00:21:04,276
Somebody all by himself, like Lindbergh crossing the Atlantic

299
00:21:04,277 --> 00:21:06,290
or Floyd Collins.

300
00:21:06,530 --> 00:21:08,697
Floyd Collins. Doesn't that ring a bell?

301
00:21:08,698 --> 00:21:11,126
No, not to me, it doesn't.

302
00:21:11,243 --> 00:21:13,077
You never heard of Floyd Collins?

303
00:21:13,078 --> 00:21:15,287
1925. Kentucky.

304
00:21:15,288 --> 00:21:17,253
The guy pinned way down in that cave.

305
00:21:17,457 --> 00:21:19,333
One of the biggest stories that ever broke.

306
00:21:19,334 --> 00:21:23,007
Front page in every paper in the country for weeks.

307
00:21:23,255 --> 00:21:26,560
Say, what'd you take at that school of journalism, advertising?

308
00:21:26,842 --> 00:21:29,260
Well, maybe I did hear about it.

309
00:21:29,261 --> 00:21:31,679
Then maybe you heard that a reporter on a Louisville paper

310
00:21:31,680 --> 00:21:35,851
crawled in for the story and came out with a Pulitzer Prize.

311
00:21:52,033 --> 00:21:55,494
Guess we'd better not fool around with that.

312
00:21:55,495 --> 00:21:57,460
Here. Hold this.

313
00:22:08,300 --> 00:22:10,347
Now let me have it.

314
00:22:11,762 --> 00:22:13,394
And camera.

315
00:22:15,098 --> 00:22:17,525
You got a couple of bulbs?

316
00:22:21,646 --> 00:22:23,493
You stay here.

317
00:22:23,523 --> 00:22:27,026
That sand gets any worse, let me hear from you, but loud.

318
00:22:27,027 --> 00:22:29,361
I don't like the looks of it, Chuck.

319
00:22:29,362 --> 00:22:31,458
I don't either, fan.

320
00:22:32,991 --> 00:22:35,122
But I like the odds.

321
00:23:00,268 --> 00:23:01,771
Hello!

322
00:23:03,021 --> 00:23:04,606
Hello!

323
00:23:04,815 --> 00:23:06,281
Here!

324
00:23:20,122 --> 00:23:21,706
Over here.

325
00:23:25,460 --> 00:23:26,927
Here.

326
00:23:29,005 --> 00:23:30,720
Over here.

327
00:23:47,190 --> 00:23:49,692
Hello, Leo. How do you feel?

328
00:23:49,693 --> 00:23:51,235
Not so bad any more.

329
00:23:51,236 --> 00:23:53,571
I thought nobody would ever come.

330
00:23:53,572 --> 00:23:56,367
Anything hurt? Any bones broken?

331
00:23:57,075 --> 00:23:59,039
No, I guess not.

332
00:23:59,161 --> 00:24:00,911
Can't you get your legs out from under?

333
00:24:00,912 --> 00:24:03,789
What do you think I've been trying to do?

334
00:24:03,790 --> 00:24:05,499
They're pinned under me.

335
00:24:05,500 --> 00:24:07,596
Maybe I can help.

336
00:24:09,671 --> 00:24:11,802
Hey, watch it! Watch it!

337
00:24:13,508 --> 00:24:15,634
You want those rocks to come down on my head?

338
00:24:15,635 --> 00:24:17,845
I didn't know they were that shaky.

339
00:24:17,846 --> 00:24:20,190
They're all pretty shaky.

340
00:24:20,348 --> 00:24:23,225
It's an old place been coming apart for a long time.

341
00:24:23,226 --> 00:24:25,478
Looks like we'll have to take them out one by one.

342
00:24:25,479 --> 00:24:29,482
Don't try it by yourself. It's gonna take a lot of figuring.

343
00:24:29,483 --> 00:24:32,777
The way they are now, if one goes, they'll all go, roof and everything.

344
00:24:32,778 --> 00:24:35,324
I see what you mean. Well, here.

345
00:24:35,781 --> 00:24:38,374
Wrap yourself in this blanket.

346
00:24:38,784 --> 00:24:42,172
And get some of this hot coffee inside of you.

347
00:24:42,370 --> 00:24:44,548
Thanks, mister.

348
00:24:44,956 --> 00:24:47,291
- Cigar. - Your wife sent them.

349
00:24:47,292 --> 00:24:51,337
She did? That's funny. She always beefs when I smoke a cigar.

350
00:24:51,338 --> 00:24:54,048
- Hey, what's your name, mister? - Charlie Tatum.

351
00:24:54,049 --> 00:24:57,936
Just driving by the trading post when I heard about it.

352
00:24:58,386 --> 00:25:00,262
Hey, what happened to those other fellows?

353
00:25:00,263 --> 00:25:02,139
I heard them, but they went away.

354
00:25:02,140 --> 00:25:03,682
Why don't they do something about getting me out?

355
00:25:03,683 --> 00:25:06,894
Easy, Leo. They'll get you out. But you know what you just said.

356
00:25:06,895 --> 00:25:09,730
It takes figuring, maybe some special equipment.

357
00:25:09,731 --> 00:25:11,398
They're not gonna leave me here overnight?

358
00:25:11,399 --> 00:25:15,528
They'll do it as fast as they can, but they got to do it right.

359
00:25:15,529 --> 00:25:19,368
Yeah, I know. Only that's a pretty heavy mountain.

360
00:25:19,699 --> 00:25:21,664
Tell me, Leo. How'd it happen?

361
00:25:21,993 --> 00:25:23,160
I...

362
00:25:23,161 --> 00:25:27,540
I guess I crawled in too far this time. You've got to, to find a good one.

363
00:25:27,541 --> 00:25:30,762
Back there, it's pretty well cleaned out.

364
00:25:31,586 --> 00:25:35,094
But I found me a beauty. Worth 50 bucks any day.

365
00:25:37,134 --> 00:25:39,596
Just then the whole floor caved in under me.

366
00:25:41,179 --> 00:25:44,520
I guess maybe they didn't want me to have it.

367
00:25:44,641 --> 00:25:46,725
They? Who are they?

368
00:25:46,726 --> 00:25:50,482
The Indian dead. They're all around here.

369
00:25:51,273 --> 00:25:54,316
This is a tomb, mister, with mummies 400 years old.

370
00:25:54,317 --> 00:25:57,361
They used to bury them here with these jars alongside,

371
00:25:57,362 --> 00:25:59,405
you know, full of corn and wampum.

372
00:25:59,406 --> 00:26:02,082
That's worthwhile knowing, Leo. Go on.

373
00:26:02,784 --> 00:26:04,084
I...

374
00:26:04,536 --> 00:26:06,454
I guess maybe they've been watching me all the time

375
00:26:06,455 --> 00:26:08,706
I've been taking things out of here and got mad.

376
00:26:08,707 --> 00:26:10,671
Bad spirits, huh?

377
00:26:13,211 --> 00:26:16,547
I guess you're gonna laugh at me, think I'm crazy.

378
00:26:16,548 --> 00:26:19,467
But when you lie down here all by yourself, you get to thinking.

379
00:26:19,468 --> 00:26:21,385
Do me a favour, will you?

380
00:26:21,386 --> 00:26:24,894
Hold up that jar again. And look at me.

381
00:26:25,056 --> 00:26:27,892
- Hey, what are you doing? - Taking your picture.

382
00:26:27,893 --> 00:26:29,525
What for?

383
00:26:30,353 --> 00:26:32,354
- Gonna put it in the paper. - What kind of paper?

384
00:26:32,355 --> 00:26:34,482
In a newspaper in Albuquerque.

385
00:26:34,483 --> 00:26:35,983
- My picture? - Certainly.

386
00:26:35,984 --> 00:26:39,236
- Honest? - Everybody'll want to see how you look.

387
00:26:39,237 --> 00:26:41,447
And I'm gonna write a story. They'll wanna know all about you.

388
00:26:41,448 --> 00:26:42,656
They'll be pulling for you.

389
00:26:42,657 --> 00:26:45,535
How do you like that? Me in a paper.

390
00:26:45,869 --> 00:26:49,258
- Let's take another one, Leo. - Oh, let me wipe my face first.

391
00:26:50,415 --> 00:26:51,964
Hold it.

392
00:26:52,250 --> 00:26:54,085
And don't say anything about those Indian spirits.

393
00:26:54,086 --> 00:26:55,795
I don't want anybody to think I'm scared.

394
00:26:55,796 --> 00:26:58,425
Don't worry, Leo. I'm your pal.

395
00:26:59,716 --> 00:27:02,343
I know. That's why I can talk to you.

396
00:27:02,344 --> 00:27:04,190
Sure, you can.

397
00:27:05,055 --> 00:27:07,973
You know, in the army, I was plenty scared, too.

398
00:27:07,974 --> 00:27:10,188
Like when my outfit landed in Italy.

399
00:27:11,269 --> 00:27:15,488
Only in the army, it's different. There, everybody's scared.

400
00:27:16,316 --> 00:27:19,455
Your barge is gonna land. You know you're gonna die.

401
00:27:20,404 --> 00:27:23,543
And then a guy starts singing, soft-like.

402
00:27:24,449 --> 00:27:29,332
Then a guy next to you starts singing. Pretty soon, you're singing, too.

403
00:27:30,831 --> 00:27:33,666
Hut-Sut Rawlson on the rillerah

404
00:27:33,667 --> 00:27:36,502
And a brawla, brawla sooit

405
00:27:36,503 --> 00:27:38,599
Hut-Sut Rawlson

406
00:27:40,340 --> 00:27:43,217
Well, it worked, didn't it? Nothing happened to you.

407
00:27:43,218 --> 00:27:46,689
Not a thing, except I got the mumps in Naples.

408
00:27:47,472 --> 00:27:49,974
Well, you light yourself a cigar, Leo. I gotta say so long.

409
00:27:49,975 --> 00:27:51,684
I certainly wish you could stay a while longer.

410
00:27:51,685 --> 00:27:55,062
So do I. But there's a lot to do outside getting things organised.

411
00:27:55,063 --> 00:27:57,858
Well, you wanna get out, don't you?

412
00:27:59,484 --> 00:28:01,485
Looks like it's gonna be a long night.

413
00:28:01,486 --> 00:28:03,738
None of that. Come on, Leo.

414
00:28:03,739 --> 00:28:06,657
Hut-Sut Rawlson on the rillerah

415
00:28:06,658 --> 00:28:08,421
And a...

416
00:28:08,702 --> 00:28:10,995
I said come on now. All together.

417
